An open letter to my clients & followers before I enter a new era 🥹🫶🏼

Important highlights: 

✨The wonderful @njkls_strong will be taking over my clients for the time being while I spend the next few months with my ~full~ attention on my family. 

✨Not sure when I’ll be back to taking on clients transactionally however I do hope to hop back into finishing my online course and offering homebuyer consultations and stategy sessions come fall! 

✨ THANK YOU so much for your support, referrals, and trust over the past 10 years. From just liking a post, watching a story, mentioning my name when real estate comes up or reaching out to buy or sell. I wouldn’t have the oppportunity to slow down if it wasn’t for you. 

✨ I had a few motivations when chosing to get into real estate; helping people and being able to make my own schedule to spend time with my future children. Although I’ve come to realize that “making your own schedule” as a Realtor is completely dependent on your clients and the market demands— I’m extremely grateful to chose to take this time off now to enjoy the few years of childhood I get with them. 

If you watch/listen to this entire video then thank and if you don’t I don’t blame you 😂 just me sapping and yapping.

latestPosts.caption:
Hi 👋  I’m Allyssa! 

✨ Realtor 
✨ Real estate educator + advisor 
✨ Landlord + investor 
✨ Scoripio ☀️ Aquarius 🌙 Aquarius ⬆️
✨ Manifesting Generator @my.humandesign 
✨ but most importantly; twin mama 

Aside from all the labels - my deep purpose in life is to help people realize their potential and give them the tools and education I’ve dug for over the years to make it a reality 🫶🏼

As I get older, I get clearer and clearer about my purpose and how I can be useful to others. 

I want to advocate and empower those who didn’t have things in life handed to them. I want to be an example of what hard work, consistency, dedication and belief in yourself can lead to. 

My life is far from perfect - obviously - but I can tell you with absolute certainty that my life would of turned out a whole lot different if I didn’t make the choice to take control of it 10 years ago. 

If I didn’t dedicate all of my free time to being curious about myself and start looking at the things in my life as opportunities instead of setbacks. 

My fiancé and I started our business 8 years ago with nothing but some credit card debt (true story) + a dream. No family ties in the industry, no trust fund or careers to fall back on. We went all in and learned how to hack the system when it comes to buying a home and we want to bring our live experience and knowledge to you in a way that’s simple and easy to understand + most importantly - realistic. 

Follow me for real estate + real life content. Take what resonates and leave the rest. Share with those you think who may need it or don’t. If I touch just one person, it was all worth it 😊

&& thank you for all your support 💛

#Realtor #HomebuyerEducation #Empower #ofService #Positivity #PersonalDevelopment #LifeJourney #IntrotoMe

And the biggest shoutout to @njkls_strong for partnering with me on this one making sure all of the logistics were handled throughout the transaction since I knew we’d be cutting it close to baby time (although no baby yet! 😅) 

Congrats to the new buyers on a beautiful home and congrats to B&S on a successful sale and being a pure example of bridging the gap between home and investment and leveraging real estate perfectly! 💸🏡🫶🏼

latestPosts.caption:
It’s funny how as a young entrepreneur one of the main motivators to work for myself was having the freedom to spend time with my future children.

And then when I had children, kind of unplanned and 2 at once nonetheless, I was overwhelmed to say the least. 

Overwhelmed with motherhood, the constant demands of 2 infants, the grief of the “old me” that I felt like jumping back into work was the only option for my sanity (and maybe it was).. postpartum is a real beast on your mental health if you didn’t know.. 

Getting back to work, and thriving, did indeed help me feel like “myself” again but it also came with a lot of sacrifice. Missing precious moments, distraction during time I was with them, more stress & responsibilities, family schedule chaos, parental role confusion, ect. 

I wonder now, being a little wiser than before, if we try to find “our old selves” again after having kids because we are uncertain of who we are becoming as a mother.. If the transition and change within comes on a little too quick for us to process fully so we run back to what we’ve always known instead of embracing the unknown.. 

Everyone’s different of course, and I am not yet postpartum, and very well could have another paradigm shift around motherhood soon, but right now these are the thoughts that are rummaging my mind as I prepare to embrace this stage in my life fully. 

Even though I am certain there will be times I want to run back to how things were, to have my own space back, to be my own person.

But the hard truth is, I will never be my own person again, I will always have 3 little shadows. 3 souls that came from mine, 3 hearts to tend to and minds to inspire to thrive and I’m learning and relearning everyday that to me, that is the most important job in the entire world, the most important “business” to tend to.

I can’t wait to dive in headfirst knowing and trusting this is where my time is best served. 

💭😌

#home #modernmotherhood #mompreneur #powerpause

latestPosts.caption:
This trend is fitting for how I’ve been feeling lately … 

I’ve noticed the way social media has been influencing my mindset around taking time off postpartum. 

Whether it be the entrepreneur moms, or postpartum workout videos, or “how to succeed in real estate as a mom” sales funnel ads 

I continually find myself reminding myself that THIS IS MY LIFE and I inherently know what’s best for me and my family right now. Other people’s experiences and choices should not concern me. The comparison is really real. 

I know that resting, in my home, for a minimum of 30 days after birth is essential. 

I know that being a “stay at home working mom” is not easy or enjoyable and comes with constant guilt and “not enoughness” (for me). 

I’m learning that my worth doesn’t lie in how much I can do for others. 

I’m relearning what family dynamic works for us and it’s not we both do everything all the time. 

I’m not willing to sacrifice the few years I have with my children as small children any longer. 

Taking time off may hinder my external & financial success but that’s not the success I’m after anymore .. 

And lastly, I’m not willing to accept that my kids should just “adjust” to my chaotic lifestyle. They didn’t choose this, I chose them and my responsibility to provide them the best possible foundation of a healthy happy life 

#unlearninghustleculture #momlife #maternityleave #momfirst #success

latestPosts.caption:
SELLERS- I get you.. 🥹

Two things can exist at once. A house can be an investment and a home. Selling can be exciting and sad. 

Yesterday’s post was about assessing risk and the financial benefits of real estate investments. 

Today’s post is to share the emotional attachment I had to this property. Not only was this our first home, where we brought our children home too, and raised them for a few years. Where we had so many highs and so many lows in our family. Where we put blood sweat and tears into renovating and maintaining. But also a property that gave us the opportunity of ownership that we didn’t think was possible for us only a few short months prior. And then it afforded us the opportunity to leverage  to buy our dream home.. truly one of the biggest blessings to ever come into my life (aside from my incredible husband and children of course). 

I think real estate is so cool and unique in the sense that it’s one of the only assets that holds such emotional value and financial value and therefore life changing potential.. ✨🏡 

Maybe it’s the pregnancy hormones — just feeling sappy today, that’s all 🥲

#realestate #home #leverage #firsthome #mademethinkofyou

latestPosts.caption:
I kinda air balled myself on this one.. 🏀😅

I’ve got a lot to say about this one so listen up 👇🏼

I don’t think there are many “right” or “wrong” moves in real estate investing (when your small scale atleast 👋) so long as you are assessing risk properly based on your personal circumstances. 

Could we have held into this property long term (30+ years) like we originally planned and seen way larger returns? Probably. 

But if you bought your property in 2021 or earlier than you are most likely seeing SUBSTANTIAL ROI rates in the shortest amount of time in history… this may never happen again in our lifetime. 

NOTE: this ROI is simply calculated based on initial investment (down payment+closing costs+renovations) vs net proceeds at closing.  This property has mostly paid for itself monthly because of the rental income it produces. 

For us, the opportunity to sell fell in our laps and looking at the investment from all angels (appreciation, ROI, capital improvements, maintenance, ect) we ultimately decided that selling was the best decision for us and our family right now that will potentially open up new opportunities down the road. 

That’s why it’s more important than ever to have the education to make these hard decisions confidently instead of following the trends and fads of big time real estate investors online. 

Real estate is one of the most complex investments you can make due to all of the factors that contribute to it being a “good investment” or not. Not to a mention, a “good investment” is going to mean different things for different reasons. 

If you interested in hearing more about why we decided to sell, or want advise on how to leverage or optimize your real estate investment or home, reach out!! 📲
